        // TODO Auto-generated method stub

        RegCentV client = new RegCentV();
        client.start();
    }

    // the default constructor you call does not set this.in, this.out or this.socket
    // calls initialize for gui fields but doesn&#39;t set in, out or socket
    public RegCentV() {
       initialize();
    }

Yet when you run the client, the run method looks like this:
    
    public void run() {
       try {
           out.println(&quot;Hello server&quot;);
           RegCentV window = new RegCentV();
           window.frame.setVisible(true);
           
           
       } catch (Exception e) {
           e.printStackTrace();
       }
   }

You are using out but out is null at this point.
if you use the other constructor you would have an out to use. But there is a problem there:

    // 
    public RegCentV(InetAddress add) throws IOException {
       this.socket = new Socket(&quot;192.168.1.17&quot;, 6060);
       this.in = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(socket.getInputStream()));
       this.out = new PrintWriter(new BufferedWriter(new OutputStreamWriter(socket.getOutputStream())), true);
       start();
    }

the other constructor starts the thread it just finished creating. (worse, if you subclass this constructor it may start it before it is done creating.)

I think that start() really doesn&#39;t belong there, but I admit this isn&#39;t the question you are asking. Just some additional advice.

Basically: you have multiple constructors but only 1 constructor does it&#39;s job. (a constructor&#39;s job is to bring the object into a stable/usable state.) You should probably merge both constructors as 1 is doing network and the other is doing gui. Or split them into 2 different classes and have each perform only their own job. (gui can own a network-client object to use/perform calls on. possibly register itself as a listener as well)

